  <h1>Home Acoustic Ontology: Complete Knowledge Base</h1>
  
  <p>Understanding residential acoustics requires familiarity with specialized terminology spanning physics, engineering, and architectural design. This comprehensive glossary defines essential concepts, metrics, materials, and techniques that acousticians, builders, and homeowners use to describe and control sound in residential environments.</p>
  
  <h2>Fundamental Acoustic Concepts</h2>
  
  <p><strong>Sound:</strong> Mechanical vibrations traveling through a medium (air, water, or solid materials) as longitudinal waves. Sound requires three components: a source (vibration), a medium for transmission, and a receiver (ear or microphone). In residential contexts, sound typically refers to audible frequencies between 20 Hz and 20,000 Hz, though infrasound (below 20 Hz) can also cause disturbance.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Frequency:</strong> The number of complete vibration cycles per second, measured in Hertz (Hz). Higher frequencies correspond to higher perceived pitch. Residential acoustics concerns the audible range, with particular attention to speech frequencies (approximately 250-4,000 Hz) and low-frequency noise from traffic, HVAC, and home theater systems (20-200 Hz).</p>
  
  <p><strong>Wavelength:</strong> The physical distance between corresponding points of consecutive wave cycles. Calculated as speed of sound (approximately 1,130 feet per second at room temperature) divided by frequency. Long wavelengths (low frequencies) diffract around obstacles and require substantial material thickness for absorption or blocking.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Decibel (dB):</strong> A logarithmic unit measuring sound level or intensity. A 10 dB increase represents a tenfold increase in sound intensity, perceived by humans as approximately twice as loud. The threshold of hearing is defined as 0 dB SPL (sound pressure level); normal conversation occurs at 60-65 dB; pain threshold is approximately 120-140 dB.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Absorption:</strong> The process by which sound energy converts to heat upon striking a material. Porous materials (fiberglass, foam, curtains) absorb sound through air movement within material pores. Absorption coefficients range from 0.0 (perfect reflection) to 1.0 (perfect absorption) and vary with frequency—most materials absorb high frequencies more effectively than low frequencies.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Reflection:</strong> Sound waves bouncing off surfaces according to the law of angle of incidence equals angle of reflection. Hard, smooth surfaces (drywall, glass, tile) reflect most sound energy; soft, irregular surfaces absorb or scatter sound. Multiple reflections create reverberation, while single strong reflections create discrete echoes.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Diffraction:</strong> The bending of sound waves around obstacles or through openings. Low frequencies diffract more readily than high frequencies, explaining why bass is audible around corners while treble is shadowed. This phenomenon affects both noise control (low-frequency noise is harder to block) and room acoustics (low frequencies distribute more uniformly).</p>
  
  <h2>Sound Isolation Metrics</h2>
  
  <p><strong>STC (Sound Transmission Class):</strong> A rating system quantifying airborne sound isolation through building partitions. <a href="https://www.astm.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ASTM E90</a> and <a href="https://www.astm.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">E413</a> define testing procedures measuring transmission loss across 16 frequencies from 125 Hz to 4,000 Hz. STC ratings range from 25 (poor, typical of single-pane windows) to 70+ (excellent, specialized studio construction). Standard interior walls achieve STC 33-38; luxury residential construction targets STC 50-55; recording studios require STC 60+.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Transmission Loss (TL):</strong> The reduction in sound level as it passes through a barrier, measured in decibels. TL varies with frequency—increasing approximately 6 dB per octave for single-layer barriers following the Mass Law. The STC rating derives from TL measurements, though it emphasizes mid-frequency performance and may not accurately represent low-frequency isolation.</p>
  
  <p><strong>IIC (Impact Insulation Class):</strong> A rating system for structure-borne sound transmission from footfalls and impacts. <a href="https://www.astm.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ASTM E492</a> and <a href="https://www.astm.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">E1007</a> define testing using a standardized tapping machine on floors. IIC ratings range from 25 (poor, bare concrete) to 85+ (excellent, floating floors with isolation). Building codes typically require IIC 50 minimum; IIC 60+ provides satisfactory isolation for most residential applications.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Delta IIC (ΔIIC):</strong> The improvement in IIC rating provided by a floor covering or treatment over a specific subfloor. This metric isolates the contribution of floor finishes from the base construction, enabling fair comparison of underlayments and flooring materials.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Mass Law:</strong> A principle stating that doubling the mass of a barrier increases sound transmission loss by approximately 6 dB. The mass law applies to single-layer homogeneous materials; multi-layer and decoupled constructions can exceed mass law predictions. Practical application: upgrading from 1/2" to 5/8" drywall improves isolation by approximately 2-3 dB; adding a second layer provides 5-6 dB improvement.</p>
  
  <h2>Room Acoustic Metrics</h2>
  
  <p><strong>NRC (Noise Reduction Coefficient):</strong> A single-number rating of a material's sound absorption, averaging absorption coefficients at 250, 500, 1,000, and 2,000 Hz. <a href="https://www.astm.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ASTM C423</a> defines testing using a reverberation chamber. NRC ranges from 0.0 (perfectly reflective, polished marble) to 1.0 (theoretically perfect absorption, though values above 1.0 are possible due to test method edge effects). Bare concrete walls achieve NRC 0.05; professional acoustic panels exceed NRC 0.90.</p>
  
  <p><strong>SAA (Sound Absorption Average):</strong> An updated single-number rating using 12 one-third octave bands from 200 Hz to 2,500 Hz, providing more comprehensive representation than NRC's four frequencies. SAA is increasingly specified in modern acoustic standards.</p>
  
  <p><strong>RT60 (Reverberation Time):</strong> The time required for sound to decay 60 dB after the source ceases, measured in seconds. Sabine's equation calculates RT60 based on room volume and total absorption. Optimal RT60 varies by room use: 0.3-0.5 seconds for speech clarity; 0.4-0.6 seconds for music listening; 1.5-2.0+ seconds for choral performance. Modern minimalist interiors often exceed 1.5 seconds, creating excessive reverberation.</p>
  
  <p><strong>EDT (Early Decay Time):</strong> An alternative reverberation metric measuring decay over the first 10 dB and extrapolating to 60 dB. EDT correlates better with perceived reverberance than RT60 for spaces with non-linear decay characteristics.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Clarity (C50, C80):</strong> Measures of early-to-late sound energy ratio, indicating speech or music clarity. C50 uses 50 milliseconds as early/late boundary (speech applications); C80 uses 80 milliseconds (music applications). Higher values indicate greater clarity; values below 0 dB suggest excessive reverberation or echoes.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Definition (D50):</strong> The percentage of total sound energy arriving within the first 50 milliseconds. Related to C50 through logarithmic transformation, D50 above 50% typically indicates adequate speech intelligibility.</p>
  
  <h2>Building Acoustic Terms</h2>
  
  <p><strong>Decoupling:</strong> Mechanical separation of building elements to prevent structure-borne sound transmission. Techniques include resilient channels, staggered studs, isolation clips, and floating floors. Decoupling breaks vibration paths that bypass airborne sound barriers.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Resilient Channel:</strong> Metal furring strips attaching drywall to studs while providing acoustic isolation through flexible mounting. Standard resilient channels provide approximately 5-10 STC points improvement over direct attachment. Proper installation requires avoiding "short circuits" where screws contact studs.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Mass-Loaded Vinyl (MLV):</strong> A flexible, high-density barrier material (typically 1-2 lb/ft²) used for sound blocking in walls, floors, and ceilings. MLV adds mass without significant rigidity, making it useful for retrofit applications and curved surfaces.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Damping:</strong> The dissipation of vibrational energy as heat. Constrained layer damping sandwiches viscoelastic material (like <a href="https://www.green-glue.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Green Glue</a>) between rigid layers, converting bending vibration to heat. Effective for low-frequency resonance control.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Flanking Path:</strong> Alternative sound transmission paths that bypass primary barriers. Common flanking paths include HVAC ducts, electrical outlets, gaps around doors, and structural connections. The weakest flanking path limits overall sound isolation.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Soffit:</strong> A dropped ceiling section, often used for HVAC, lighting, or acoustic treatment. Acoustic soffits filled with insulation and covered with fabric provide low-frequency absorption and visual interest.</p>
  
  <h2>Acoustic Treatment Types</h2>
  
  <p><strong>Absorption Panel:</strong> A flat panel of porous absorbent material (fiberglass, mineral wool, foam) covered with acoustically transparent fabric. Wall-mounted panels address first reflections and reduce reverberation. Thicker panels (4-6 inches) absorb lower frequencies than thin panels (1-2 inches).</p>
  
  <p><strong>Bass Trap:</strong> Acoustic treatment specifically targeting low frequencies. Porous bass traps use thick absorption (6-12+ inches) in corners where pressure builds. Resonant bass traps (membrane or diaphragmatic) use tuned cavities to absorb specific frequencies with less physical depth.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Diffuser:</strong> An acoustic treatment scattering sound reflections in multiple directions rather than absorbing energy. Quadratic Residue Diffusers (QRD), Skyline diffusers, and polycylindrical diffusers maintain room liveliness while preventing discrete echoes. Diffusion preserves acoustic energy while eliminating audible artifacts.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Cloud:</strong> Suspended acoustic panels hung horizontally below ceilings. Clouds address ceiling reflections while maintaining architectural openness and lighting flexibility.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Acoustic Baffle:</strong> Vertical hanging absorbers suspended from ceilings, common in commercial and industrial spaces. Baffles provide absorption on both sides in spaces where wall treatment is impractical.</p>
  
  <h2>Sound Measurement and Analysis</h2>
  
  <p><strong>SPL (Sound Pressure Level):</strong> The local pressure deviation from ambient atmospheric pressure caused by a sound wave, measured in decibels relative to 20 micropascals (the threshold of human hearing). SPL meters measure sound levels for compliance, environmental assessment, and room tuning.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Frequency Response:</strong> A measurement showing sound level across the frequency spectrum. Flat frequency response indicates equal reproduction of all frequencies; peaks and dips indicate coloration. Room frequency response varies dramatically with position due to modal effects.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Waterfall Plot:</strong> A three-dimensional visualization showing frequency response over time. Waterfall plots reveal modal ringing—sustained resonance at specific frequencies indicating room acoustic problems requiring treatment.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Impulse Response:</strong> A measurement of how a space responds to an instantaneous sound (like a balloon pop or special test signal). Impulse response contains information about reflections, reverberation, and frequency response used for room analysis and digital correction.</p>
  
  <p><strong>NC Curve (Noise Criteria):</strong> Standardized curves for specifying acceptable background noise levels in buildings. NC ratings (NC-20, NC-30, etc.) represent curves; measured octave band levels are compared to curves to determine rating. Residential bedrooms typically target NC-25 to NC-30; home theaters target NC-30 or lower.</p>
  
  <p><strong>RC Curve (Room Criteria):</lf> Similar to NC but with additional requirements for spectral balance and low-frequency noise. RC Mark II includes requirements for sound quality, not just level.</p>
  
  <h2>Audio and Home Theater Terms</h2>
  
  <p><strong>Sweet Spot:</strong> The listening position providing optimal frequency response, imaging, and soundstage in a room. The sweet spot is typically centered between stereo speakers at approximately 1.2 times the speaker separation distance.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Imaging:</strong> The perceived spatial localization of sound sources within a stereo or surround field. Good imaging allows listeners to point to specific instrument locations. Imaging depends on speaker quality, placement, and room reflections.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Soundstage:</strong> The perceived three-dimensional space containing reproduced sound. Width, depth, and height of the soundstage contribute to listening immersion. Room acoustics significantly affect soundstage perception.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Boundary Reinforcement:</strong> Bass increase when speakers are placed near room boundaries (walls, corners, floor). Each adjacent boundary adds approximately 3 dB of low-frequency output. While this can extend bass response, it also excites room modes.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Subwoofer:</strong> A loudspeaker dedicated to low-frequency reproduction, typically below 80-120 Hz. Subwoofers handle the frequency range where room modes are most problematic and where main speakers may have limited output.</p>
  
  <h2>Conclusion</h2>
  
  <p>This glossary provides foundation for understanding residential acoustics discourse. Whether communicating with contractors, evaluating product specifications, or researching solutions, familiarity with these terms enables effective participation in acoustic design decisions. The field continues evolving with new materials, measurement techniques, and understanding of psychoacoustics—this vocabulary provides the framework for continued learning.</p>

